The first part of the course focuses on the long-run macroeconomic phenomena like long-run income levels and economic growth in the context of Solow model and its extensions, and explores also the role of decisions made by households' and firms at microeconomic level. The second part of the course deals with short-run macroeconomics, seeking for the explanations and determinants of business cycles (like wage and price rigidity). The third part of the course introduces selected building blocks of the macroeconomic model (consumption and investment, unemployment and inflation) in order to form the basis for analysing the essence and effects of monetary and fiscal policies.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to introduce theories which explain the factors behind the long-term economic growth and the short-term business fluctuations, and on this basis to analyse the possible effects of monetary and fiscal policies.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course the student has acquired the following skills and competencies:
* understands the distinction between long-run and short-run macroeconomics;
* understands the mechanism of Solow growth model and its importance in explaining long-term growth;
* Is familiar with the role of households' and firms' decisions in shaping macroeconomic equilibrium;
* knows and is able to implement real business cycle theory and other theories (e.g. Keynesioan approach and alternative explanations of incomplete nominal adjustments) in explaining short-term economic fluctuations;
* knows alternative theories of consumption and investments;
* understands the reasons of unemployment and is familiar with theories explainig the factors of unemployment;
* is able to analyse the the possible effects of monetary and fiscal policies.
